description.narrative:
&nbsp;
The tea plantation community - i.e. descendants of migrant labour brought to Sri Lanka during British Rule - in Sri Lanka has been marginalised comparatively to the rest of the population. PREDO aspires to strengthen the democratic culture with attributes of good governance among the plantation community. Enabling the presently disempowered community to stand up as rightful citizens, to make a voice to eliminate discriminations and irregularities in services. 
&nbsp;
PREDO encourages and empowers plantation communities to participate in the democratic system while empowering women to take leadership and decision making in social and political spheres through affirmative actions. By sensitising the plantation community to eliminate GBV and recognise the value of male and female participation in all spaces of life, PREDO envisions a society that upholds and nourishes human values, democratic principles for advancement of socio-cultural and economic wellbeing of families and communities in the plantation. 
&nbsp;
PREDO empowers and mobilize individuals, families and communities in the plantations and neighbouring villages, to become active agents for their own development, reduce dependence and increase self-worth to live in harmony and dignity where children and women are safe and enjoy rights. 
&nbsp;
Focus areas include &ndash; enabling access to mainstream development through strengthening democratic rights and civil society; increase women&rsquo;s political participation at the community, local and provincial level; eliminate GBV and recognise the values of women&rsquo;s contribution to the community; create awareness on climate change and its implications so that plantation community is not further exploited or discriminated on environmental issues
&nbsp;
Thematic area Gender Equality, Democracy, Conflict and justice.
